This is the semantic for an actual allocation of space in a LAYOUT. Specifically, it is an offset and orientation of a LAYOUT OBJECT's reference frame within a LAYOUT SPACE's reference frame.

A LAYOUT requires two ingredients: Space, and objects requesting space allocation. An example may be 5000 square feet within a facility, and various machines needing arrangement.
Given these ingredients, a layout is a collection of placements - a reference frame attached to each layout object is offset and oriented within a reference frame attached to the space.
A boundary decision was to focus exclusively on manufacturing, so we care about movement of physical goods throughout a manufacturing process, hence the semantic LAYOUT FOR MOVEMENT AND ACCESS.

In the context of a Layout for Movement and Access, LAYOUT OBJECT is an abstract superclass for its 'forMovement' and 'withAccess' subclasses. It is one of two layout ingredients - these are objects requesting space allocation. Any Layout Object has a GEOMETRY, which comes with a reference frame, needed for the placement.

A Layout Object With Access may be a department or a workstation ... any object which has input/output of material moving from/to other such objects. The interface between a Layout Object For Movement (e.g. aisle) and a Layout Object With Access (e.g. department) is modeled by an INTERFACE POINT.

A Layout Object For Movement may be an aisle, conveyor, overhead crane path ... any object enabling material movement among Layout Objects With Access. The interface between a Layout Object For Movement (e.g. aisle) and a Layout Object With Access (e.g. department) is modeled by an INTERFACE POINT.

An Interface Point is a simplification of the notion of "access" to a single point. It is a composite part of a Layout Object With Access, and its location is defined in that object's reference frame. An Interface Point is the interface between 'withAccess' and 'forMovement' Layout Objects, and any Layout Object For Movement should reference all incident Interface Points.

Contract Net Protocol (CNP) is a task-sharing protocol in multi-agent systems, consisting of a collection of nodes or software agents that form the `contract net'. Each node on the network can, at different times or for different tasks, be a manager or a contractor.
When a node gets a `composite task' (or for any reason cannot solve the present task) it breaks the problem down into sub-tasks (if possible) and announces the sub-task to the contract net acting as a manager. Bids are then received from potential contractors and the winning contractor(s) are awarded the job(s).

The average actual cycle time consistently achieved to fulfill customer orders. For each individual order, this cycle time starts from the order receipt and ends with customer acceptance of the order.

The percentage of orders meeting delivery performance with complete and accurate documentation and no delivery damage. Components include all items and quantities on-time using the customer's definition of on-time, and documentation - packing slips, bills of lading, invoices, etc.

This is the first-stage M2M transformation. The result is a collection of path segments and path intersections. Path segments may have incident INTERFACE POINTS plus ENDPOINT NODES and INTERNAL NODES. Path intersections may have ENDPOINT NODES.

- When two rectangular paths intersect in their interiors, four path segments and one path intersection result. Defining this partition may be manually done by the layout architect, or this can follow from a geometric shared-space analysis. Incident interface points must also be partitioned among the resulting path segments.

- Our abstraction for the network within a rectangular path segment is pictured. Computing (x,y,z) of the endpoint and internal nodes might be tricky because they must be expressed in the SPACE's reference frame.

- Our abstraction for the network within an rectangular path intersection is pictured (for a special case). Computing (x,y,z) of the endpoint nodes might be tricky because they must be expressed in the SPACE's reference frame.

- A new network results.

-- NODES are either incident interface points, endpoint nodes, or internal nodes.

-- Given a rectangular path segment and its incident INTERFACE POINTS, this completely determines the internal arcs (each ARC is a pair of directed arcs). Given a subclass of TwoRectangularPathIntersection (pictured is T-shaped), this completely determines the internal arcs. Note that knowledge of ARCS at this stage is only defined-by-picture and not yet captured in SysML semantics.
